  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe loop-vectorizer crashes on an
assertion in LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF(): (BestFactor.Width ==
LegacyVF.Width || planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...)) && \" VPlan cost
model and legacy cost model disagreed\". For the provided loop, the new
VPlan-based cost model selects a scalable VF=<vscale x 2>, while the legacy cost
model selects VF=<vscale x 4>. The assertion expects that if the VFs differ, the
chosen VPlan must contain additional simplifications that justify the
discrepancy. planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() returned false, so the
assertion fired.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug-only output gives no
intermediate logs (debug-only disabled), but from inspection in the debugger we
see: BestFactor.Width = <vscale x 2>, LegacyVF.Width = <vscale x 4>. The IR shows
a conditional branch with a constant false condition in the loop header, and a
latch PHI whose one incoming edge (from the header directly to latch) is actually
unreachable. This is a simplification opportunity (constant-folded branch + dead
incoming edge). The VPlan construction can omit the dead conditional branch,
reducing cost for certain VFs. The legacy cost model, however, precomputes branch
costs uniformly (precomputeCosts adds all branch terminators except the latch),
and marks them skipped. Because planContainsAdditionalSimplifications filters out
instructions that are marked skipped in CostCtx (SkipCostComputation), it fails
to recognize that the conditional branch eliminated from the VPlan is indeed an
extra simplification\u2014thus it returns false.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nFunction planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() (lines 7280-7324)
collects all underlying IR instructions represented by VPlan recipes, then scans
original loop instructions, treating any non-PHI that is neither represented nor
skipped for cost computation as evidence of additional simplifications. The
eliminated constant conditional branch was pre-costed and therefore added to
SkipCostComputation, causing the predicate (!SeenInstrs.contains(&I) &&
!CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true)) to be false, incorrectly hiding the
simplification. This leads to the assertion failure when cost models disagree for
VF choice solely due to that simplification.\n\nThus, the detection logic is too
strict: it suppresses recognition of simplifications for instructions that were
costed (and then marked skipped) but structurally removed by the VPlan.
Specifically, constant-folded conditional branches become absent from VPlan
recipes yet are excluded by skipCostComputation.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s):\nEdit LoopVectorize.cpp lines 7318-7322 inside
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications. Add a special-case: if an original
instruction is a conditional BranchInst with a constant condition and it is not
in SeenInstrs (i.e., removed in the VPlan), we treat it as an additional
simplification regardless of skipCostComputation. This correctly identifies
simplifications from constant-folded control flow and prevents spurious assertion
failures.\n\nProposed code change (conceptual diff):\nWithin the inner lambda
currently:\n  if (isa<PHINode>(&I)) return false;\n  return
!SeenInstrs.contains(&I) && !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true);\nReplace
with:\n  if (isa<PHINode>(&I)) return false;\n  if (auto *BI =
dyn_cast<BranchInst>(&I)) {\n    if (BI->isConditional() &&
isa<ConstantInt>(BI->getCondition()) &&\n        !SeenInstrs.contains(&I))\n
return true; // Constant-folded branch eliminated in VPlan.\n  }\n  return
!SeenInstrs.contains(&I) && !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true);\n\nRationale:
We only relax the skipCostComputation gating for a precise pattern (conditional
branch with constant condition removed from VPlan). This prevents false positives
while covering the demonstrated failing case.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash
results from the oversight in planContainsAdditionalSimplifications that misses
simplifications of constant conditional branches due to their prior cost
precomputation. The fix adds explicit detection of eliminated constant
conditional branches, allowing the assertion to pass when the VPlan legitimately
differs from legacy cost modeling because of such simplifications. This resolves
the abort for the given reproducer and aligns the assertion condition with real
simplification scenarios.",
